The '''Office of Seed and Plant Introduction''' was a branch of the [[United States Department of Agriculture]] which introduced over 200,000 [[species]] and [[Plant variety (law)|varieties]] of [[exotic species|non-native]] [[plant]]s to the [[United States]].<ref>Carson, Rachel. ''Silent Spring'' (Boston: Houghton Mifflin, 1962), Mariner Books, 2002, {{ISBN|0-618-24906-0}}</ref>  It was established in 1898, under the direction of [[David Fairchild]]. The department employed agricultural explorers to seek out economically useful plant species to import to the United States. One of the agency's explorers, [[Frank Nicholas Meyer]], introduced the variety of [[Meyer lemon|lemon]] which was later named after him.

