{{Infobox book | italic title = | name = Unstoppable: Harnessing Science to Change the World | image = Unstoppable book cover.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | author = [[Bill Nye]] | audio_read_by = | title_orig = | orig_lang_code = | title_working = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | release_number = | subject = [[Environmental science]] | genre = [[Nonfiction]] | set_in = | published = | publisher = [[St. Martin's Press]] | publisher2 = | pub_date = 2015 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 352 | awards = | isbn = 978-1250007148 | isbn_note = | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = [[Undeniable: Evolution and the Science of Creation]] | followed_by = | native_wikisource = | wikisource = | notes = | exclude_cover = | website = }} '''''Unstoppable: Harnessing Science to Change the World''''' is a 2015 [[book]] written by [[Bill Nye]] and edited by [[Corey S. Powell]]. Published by [[St. Martin's Press]], it is Nye's second book, after ''[[Undeniable: Evolution and the Science of Creation]]'', also with Powell, which was also published by St. Martin's Press in 2014.<ref name="AP">{{cite news |last1=Kay |first1=Jennifer |title=Review: Bill Nye tackles climate change in new book|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20151109/us--book-review-unstoppable/ |accessdate=5 January 2017|work=The Huffington Post|agency=Associated Press |date=9 November 2015}}</ref> The book is about how to use [[Environmental science|science to improve the environment]] and the challenges faced with [[global warming]] as well as raising the standard of living.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Unstoppable: A Conversation with Bill Nye the Science Guy |url = https://www.fi.edu/special-events/unstoppable-conversation-bill-nye-science-guy |publisher=[[Franklin Institute]] |accessdate = 2015-11-04}}{{dead link|fix-attempted=yes|date=January 2017}}</ref>
== Reception == [[BBC Future Media|BBC]] science columnist Rose Eveleth wrote a joint review in ''The New York Times'' of the audiobook versions of ''Unstoppable'' and [[Leonard Mlodinow]]'s 2015 book ''[[The Upright Thinkers]]''. Eveleth found Nye's audiobook "easy to listen to", noting the familiarity of Nye's voice to those who have watched the children's television series ''[[Bill Nye the Science Guy]]''. However, Eveleth wrote that both books "stumble" because they "recycle well-known material", describing how Nye "spends a good chunk of his book talking about the setup of his extremely energy-efficient home ... Some of these stories are relevant and interesting. Other times, they feel forced, as if both authors knew that without a personal touch, their books would read like any other general primer on climate change or great men in science."<ref name="NYT">{{cite news |last1=Eveleth|first1=Rose|title='The Upright Thinkers' and 'Unstoppable'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/22/books/review/the-upright-thinkers-and-unstoppable.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=23 January 2017 |date=18 May 2016}}</ref> Simon Warthall, in the introduction to an interview with Nye for ''[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]''{{'}}s "Book Talk" column, commented that ''Unstoppable'' "mixes science and [Nye's] trademark humor".<ref name="natgeo">{{cite web |last1=Worrall |first1=Simon |title=Bill Nye the Science Guy Knows How to Fix Climate Change|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/2015/11/151115-bill-nye-science-guy-climate-change-unstoppable-ngbooktalk/ |website=[[National Geographic Society|National Geographic]] |accessdate=23 January 2017 |date=15 November 2015}}</ref> Jennifer Kay, in a review for the [[Associated Press]], commented on the clarity of Nye's language, writing how "Nye explains the basics of climate science without making 'Unstoppable' feel like a textbook."<ref name="AP" />
